Hello Emmanuele:

Thanks for the quick response. Here is part of the code from the tinyb project-(I am not the author of tinyb)-that is causing the problem:

From the file BluetoothManager.cpp

```cpp
class tinyb::BluetoothEventManager {
public:
    static void on_interface_added (GDBusObject *object,
        GDBusInterface *interface, gpointer user_data) {
        GDBusInterfaceInfo *info = g_dbus_interface_get_info(interface);
        BluetoothType type = BluetoothType::NONE;
        BluetoothManager *manager = BluetoothManager::get_bluetooth_manager();

        /* Unknown interface, ignore */
        if (info == NULL)
            return;
```

@aklapper as @ernestask also stated there is a way to create files using templates saved in the template dir. 
Obviously "create a text file" was only an example. I create tons of templated files, like Writer's documents, Calc's sheets, PHP/C++ preformatted files, and so on.

This is a bug for Nautilus 3.30 and should be reopened.

@afranke The new code, by default, proxies the request to Gravatar. In other words, the user IP is hidden behind Libravatar.
However, you can also completely disable use of Gravatar by adding &gravatarproxy=n&gravatarredirect=n to the URL.
I hope that answer helps!

@tobiasmue You're right: Libravatar is more or less just another 3rd party tool someone can trust; Or not.
Before I became the 'lead software developer' of Libravatar, I trusted them more than Gravatar, since there is no big company behind it and no external tracking JS was used and the code was Open Source. That all is still true, the only difference is that I know the source code now much better :-)

Anyway, I'm happy you're not opposing against this and I'm happy to see Libravatar in use on Gnome GIT instance, hopefully, soon.

